Africa
------
[2] Uganda (multi-districts)
Date: Tue 6 Dec 2011
Source: Sunday Monitor [edited]
http://www.monitor.co.ug/News/National/-/688334/1284858/-/bg76r3z/-/index.html


Government issues national measles alert
----------------------------------------
The Ministry of Health yesterday announced that there is a national
measles outbreak in eastern, central, and western Uganda, warning the
public to report suspected cases early.

The director-general of health services in the ministry, Dr Jane Ruth
Aceng, said in a statement that they have identified cases in Bududa,
Bukedea, Bushenyi Kabarole, Kampala, Rakai, Ntungamo, Luweero,
Namayingo, Nakasongola, and Namutumba districts.

The contagious disease was first suspected in Namayingo in November
[2011] after a total of 112 children were admitted with measles
symptoms. To curb the airborne disease, Dr Aceng said they had opened
up a measles unit at the National Referral Hospital, Mulago, and other
upcountry hospitals and health centres to attend to any reported
cases. She warned the public to "avoid and immediately take any
suspected measles cases to the nearest health facility."

Although reported cases of measles in Uganda have declined by over 90
per cent, due in part to the initiation of nationwide vaccination
campaigns in 2003, it continues to claim more lives of children than
any other vaccine-preventable disease.

Dr Edward Mwesigwa, the Bushenyi district health officer, said 4 cases
had been identified in that district. He identified the type of
measles as German rubella [that is, German measles caused by Rubella
virus], which broke out 2 weeks ago before they reported the case to
the Ministry of Health. They sent samples and the disease was
confirmed, he said. [It is presumed that the measles cases reported
elsewhere in the country have been caused by measles virus infection,
and not by rubella virus. - Mod.CP]

Measles is highly contagious and can rapidly spread among children who
are not immunised. While measles does not kill, it can cause
blindness, malnutrition, deafness or pneumonia.

In Ntungamo, Mr Rodgers Kizito, the district cold chain officer --
responsible for immunisation services -- said there was one case of
measles in the district early November in Rweikiniro Sub-county. The
victim is said to have contracted the measles in Kampala. "She was
treated and she recovered; none of her family members contracted the
disease," Mr Kizito said, adding that there is a large number of
children in Ntungamo who are not immunised which increases their
susceptibility to measles.

(byline: Risdel Kasasora)

