Oceania
-------
[4] New Zealand (Tairawhiti)
Date: Mom 5 Dec 2011
Surce: The Gisborne Herlad [abbreviated & edited]
http://www.gisborneherald.co.nz/article/?id=25644


Four more measles cases
-----------------------
A second wave of measles has broken out in Tairawhiti. Two East Coast
children and two Gisborne teenagers presented with measles-like
symptoms at the weekend. Test results due later this week are "very
probable" to confirm measles, says Tairawhiti District Health (TDH)
medical officer of health, Dr Geoffrey Cramp. The 4 new cases come
less than a fortnight after a boy at Gisborne Intermediate [school]
and a boy at Campion College were confirmed as having contracted
measles.

"Between them, these 4 new cases have been in contact with hundreds of
people. Those most at risk are non-immunised people, babies, pregnant
mothers and those with weakened immune systems. I cannot stress enough
the importance of immediate immunisation."

TDH has established an emergency operations centre to manage the
situation. TDH will also ensure non-immunised people who have had
contact with these cases stay away from work or school. Dr Cramp
advises people with measles symptoms to phone their doctors prior to
arrival, so arrangements can be made for them to be put into an
isolated room. "This is very important -- the sick person needs to
stay outside the clinic, until staff are ready to take them to the
isolated area. We all need to take responsibility to limit the spread
of this horrible disease.

"If you are unwell and think you have the measles phone your GP, or
call Healthline on 0800 611 116 for free advice from a registered
nurse. It is very important that you stay away from school and stay
away from work."

